\section{Translation Prompt Template}
\label{sec:appendix-prompt}

This appendix reproduces the full translation prompt template used by the
evaluation pipeline. All prompts follow this structure; only the source code
content, target API, and file lists vary between tasks. The anonymization
protocol described in Section~\ref{sec:eval-pipeline} is applied before
prompt construction.

\subsection{System Message}

The system message is identical for all translation tasks:

\begin{lstlisting}[language={},caption={System message template. \texttt{\{src\_api\}} and \texttt{\{tgt\_api\}} are replaced with API display names (e.g., ``CUDA'', ``OpenMP''). \texttt{\{tgt\_lang\}} is the target language hint (e.g., ``cpp'', ``c'').},label={lst:system-msg}]
You are a parallel programming expert
specializing in {src_api} to {tgt_api}
translation. Translate the provided source
code to {tgt_api}. Output ONLY the translated
code, no explanations. For each file, output
a markdown code fence with the filename on
the opening line:

```{tgt_lang} filename={filename}
<code>
```

Preserve the algorithm, I/O behavior, data
formats, and output format exactly. The
translated code must compile with the
provided build command.
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{User Message Structure}

The user message is assembled from the following sections, in order:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Translation Task} --- source API, target API. Kernel name and
  benchmark description are \emph{not} included (anonymization).
\item \textbf{Target Files to Produce} --- list of anonymized target filenames
  (e.g., \texttt{translated\_0.cpp}, \texttt{translated\_1.cl}).
\item \textbf{Build Command} --- the anonymized compilation command in a code
  fence, so the LLM can ensure API and flag compatibility.
\item \textbf{Source Code} --- each source file presented as a numbered
  subsection (\texttt{Source File 1}, \texttt{Source File 2}, \ldots) with
  comments stripped.
\item \textbf{Support / Header Files} (optional) --- genericized header and
  support files from the source directory, with an instruction to inline
  definitions rather than emit unresolvable \texttt{\#include} directives.
\item \textbf{Target Infrastructure Context} (optional) --- non-kernel target
  files provided as read-only reference so the LLM can match expected function
  signatures and data structures. Marked ``DO NOT MODIFY.''
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Anonymization Details}

Three anonymization steps are applied before prompt construction:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Comment stripping.} All C/C++ comments (\texttt{//} and
  \texttt{/* */}) are removed from source files to prevent benchmark-specific
  annotations from leaking into the prompt.
\item \textbf{Filename genericization.} Target filenames are replaced with
  \texttt{translated\_0.ext}, \texttt{translated\_1.ext}, etc. Source files
  are labeled \texttt{Source File 1}, \texttt{Source File 2}. An internal
  mapping restores original filenames when writing LLM output to disk.
\item \textbf{Build command anonymization.} Kernel-specific identifiers are
  stripped from the build command string.
\end{itemize}

